State Machine\n1. **Pending**: URL discovered, added to `queue` table.\n2. **Processing**: URL pulled from `queue` by `_indexer`, state updated to `processing`.\n3. **Done**: URL processed by `_worker`, state updated to `done`.\n- **Duplicate Prevention**: `url` is the `PRIMARY KEY` in the `queue` table. `INSERT OR IGNORE` ensures a URL is never queued twice.\n\n## 4. Search & Crawl Concurrency\n- **Search**: Executes as a read-only `SELECT` statement. It does not require the `db_lock`, allowing it to run concurrently with crawler write operations.\n- **Back-pressure**: The `memory_queue` is bounded at 100 items. The `_indexer` only fetches new URLs when the queue has space, preventing memory exhaustion.\n\n## 5. Technical Constraints\n- **HTTP**: `aiohttp.ClientSession` is the exclusive HTTP client.\n- **Database**: `sqlite3` with `PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL`.\n- **Output**: ASCII-safe characters only.\n- **Lifecycle**: All background work is managed via `asyncio.create_task` and tracked in a `set` for graceful cancellation.\n```", text="FILE: architecture.md\n```text\n# Architecture Design: Mini Search Engine\n\nThis system implements a resilient, single-loop asynchronous crawler and search engine. It adheres to strict concurrency constraints, ensuring non-blocking I/O and thread-safe database operations.\n\n## 1. Core Components & Public APIs\n\n### database.py\n- **`Database(db_path)`**: Initializes SQLite in WAL mode.\n- **`add_to_queue(urls, depth)`**: Batch inserts URLs into the `queue` table using `INSERT OR IGNORE` to enforce uniqueness.\n- **`mark_processing(url)` / `mark_done(url)`**: Updates URL state to manage the lifecycle.\n- **`save_page(url, title, body, origin_url, depth)`**: Persists crawled content.\n- **`search(query)`**: Performs a non-blocking `SELECT` query via `asyncio.to_thread`.\n- **`get_pending(limit)`**: Retrieves URLs for the crawler to process.\n- **`set_setting(key, value)`**: Persists configuration settings.\n\n### crawler_service.py\n- **`CrawlerService(db, worker_count)`**: Manages the crawler lifecycle.\n- **`start_in_background(seed_url, max_depth)`**: Orchestrates the `_engine` task.\n- **`_worker(session)`**: Consumes from `memory_queue`, fetches HTML, parses links, and updates DB.\n- **`_indexer(max_depth)`**: Monitors `queue` table and populates `memory_queue` (back-pressure: maxsize=100).\n\n### main.py\n- **`main()`**: Entry point. Manages the `asyncio` event loop and CLI interaction.\n- **CLI**: Uses `asyncio.to_thread(input, ...)` to prevent blocking the event loop during user interaction.\n\n## 2. Event Loop & Concurrency Model\n- **Single Loop**: All operations run on the main thread's `asyncio` event loop.\n- **Threading**: `threading.Thread` is forbidden. Blocking SQLite operations are offloaded to the default `ThreadPoolExecutor` via `asyncio.to_thread`.\n- **Locking**: A single `asyncio.Lock` is shared across all write operations to prevent SQLite write contention.\n\n## 3. URL Lifecycle & State Machine\n1. **Pending**: URL discovered, added to `queue` table.\n2. **Processing**: URL pulled from `queue` by `_indexer`, state updated to `processing`.\n3. **Done**: URL processed by `_worker`, state updated to `done`.\n- **Duplicate Prevention**: `url` is the `PRIMARY KEY` in the `queue` table. `INSERT OR IGNORE` ensures a URL is never queued twice.\n\n## 4. Search & Crawl Concurrency\n- **Search**: Executes as a read-only `SELECT` statement. It does not require the `db_lock`, allowing it to run concurrently with crawler write operations.\n- **Back-pressure**: The `memory_queue` is bounded at 100 items. The `_indexer` only fetches new URLs when the queue has space, preventing memory exhaustion.\n\n## 5. Technical Constraints\n- **HTTP**: `aiohttp.ClientSession` is the exclusive HTTP client.\n- **Database**: `sqlite3` with `PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL`.\n- **Output**: ASCII-safe characters only.\n- **Lifecycle**: All background work is managed via `asyncio.create_task` and tracked in a `set` for graceful cancellation.\n```")
