 ensures that if the crawler produces URLs faster than workers can process them, the producer suspends (`await queue.put()`), preventing memory exhaustion.\n\n## 5. Concurrent Search and Crawl\n- Search operations are non-blocking `SELECT` queries on the SQLite database.\n- Since SQLite is in WAL mode, readers (search) do not block writers (crawler).\n- The `asyncio.Lock` in `database.py` only serializes write operations, ensuring data integrity without stalling the search functionality.\n```', text='FILE: architecture.md\n```text\n# System Architecture: Async Mini Search Engine\n\n## 1. Single-Event-Loop Lifecycle\nThe system operates on a single `asyncio` event loop initialized in `main.py`. All components (CLI, Crawler, Database) are designed as `async` services that register tasks via `asyncio.create_task`. No secondary threads are spawned. The lifecycle is managed by `asyncio.run()`, ensuring graceful shutdown of the crawler and database connection upon SIGINT/SIGTERM.\n\n## 2. Public APIs\n\n### database.py\n- `Database(db_path: str)`: Initializes connection, enables WAL mode, and creates schema.\n- `async def insert_page(url: str, content: str)`: Writes crawled data. Protected by `asyncio.Lock`.\n- `async def search(query: str) -> list[dict]`: Performs a `LIKE` query on the index.\n- `async def is_crawled(url: str) -> bool`: Checks if URL exists in the index.\n\n### crawler_service.py\n- `Crawler(db: Database, max_workers: int, queue_size: int)`: Manages the crawl state.\n- `async def enqueue(url: str)`: Adds URL to the `asyncio.Queue` if not already crawled.\n- `async def run()`: Spawns `max_workers` consumer tasks that process the queue.\n- `async def stop()`: Signals workers to terminate.\n\n### main.py\n- `async def main()`: Orchestrates the startup of the `Database` and `Crawler`.\n- `async def cli_loop()`: Provides an ASCII-only interface for user input (search) and status monitoring.\n\n## 3. Crawl State Transitions\n- `pending`: URL added to `asyncio.Queue`.\n- `processing`: Worker pops URL, performs `aiohttp` request, and parses content.\n- `done`: URL inserted into SQLite; marked as visited in the internal `set` to prevent re-queueing.\n\n## 4. Duplicate Prevention and Back-pressure\n- **Duplicate Prevention**: An `asyncio.Lock` protects a `set` of visited URLs. Before adding to the queue, the crawler checks this set and the database.\n- **Back-pressure**: The `asyncio.Queue(maxsize=N)` ensures that if the crawler produces URLs faster than workers can process them, the producer suspends (`await queue.put()`), preventing memory exhaustion.\n\n## 5. Concurrent Search and Crawl\n- Search operations are non-blocking `SELECT` queries on the SQLite database.\n- Since SQLite is in WAL mode, readers (search) do not block writers (crawler).\n- The `asyncio.Lock` in `database.py` only serializes write operations, ensuring data integrity without stalling the search functionality.\n```')
