base.is_crawled(url)`. A local `set` of "in-flight" URLs is maintained to prevent duplicate processing of URLs currently in the queue.\n- Back-pressure: The `asyncio.Queue` is initialized with `maxsize`. If the queue is full, the producer (crawler logic) will naturally suspend until workers consume items, preventing memory exhaustion.\n\n## 5. Concurrent Search and Crawl\n- Search operations are non-blocking `SELECT` queries on the SQLite database.\n- Since SQLite is in WAL (Write-Ahead Logging) mode, readers do not block writers, and writers do not block readers.\n- The `asyncio.Lock` in `database.py` ensures that multiple concurrent writes (from crawler workers) are serialized, while search queries remain performant and responsive during crawl operations.\n```', text='FILE: architecture.md\n```text\n# System Architecture: Async Mini Search Engine\n\n## 1. Single-Event-Loop Lifecycle\nThe system operates on a single `asyncio` event loop initialized in `main.py`. All components (CLI, Crawler, Database) are designed as awaitable services that share this loop. No `threading` or `multiprocessing` is permitted.\n\n- Startup: `main.py` initializes the `Database` (WAL mode), then the `CrawlerService`.\n- Execution: `main.py` runs an `asyncio.gather` or `create_task` loop to manage the CLI input and the Crawler worker pool concurrently.\n- Shutdown: `main.py` triggers a graceful shutdown, awaiting the `CrawlerService` to finish current requests and closing the `Database` connection.\n\n## 2. Public APIs\n\n### database.py\n- `Database(db_path: str)`: Initializes connection, enables WAL mode, and ensures schema exists.\n- `async def insert_document(url: str, content: str)`: Thread-safe write using `asyncio.Lock`.\n- `async def search(query: str) -> List[Dict]`: Read-only query execution.\n- `async def is_crawled(url: str) -> bool`: Checks if URL exists in the index.\n\n### crawler_service.py\n- `CrawlerService(db: Database, max_workers: int, queue_size: int)`: Manages state.\n- `async def start(start_urls: List[str])`: Spawns worker tasks.\n- `async def worker()`: Consumes from `asyncio.Queue`, fetches via `aiohttp`, and writes to `Database`.\n\n### main.py\n- `async def main()`: Orchestrates the lifecycle.\n- `async def cli_loop()`: Handles user input (search/crawl commands) without blocking the crawler.\n\n## 3. Crawl State Transitions\n- Pending: URL added to `asyncio.Queue`.\n- Processing: URL popped from queue, `aiohttp` request in progress.\n- Done: Content written to `Database` and URL added to the "crawled" set (or checked via `db.is_crawled`).\n\n## 4. Duplicate Prevention and Back-pressure\n- Duplicate Prevention: Before adding a URL to the queue, the system checks `Database.is_crawled(url)`. A local `set` of "in-flight" URLs is maintained to prevent duplicate processing of URLs currently in the queue.\n- Back-pressure: The `asyncio.Queue` is initialized with `maxsize`. If the queue is full, the producer (crawler logic) will naturally suspend until workers consume items, preventing memory exhaustion.\n\n## 5. Concurrent Search and Crawl\n- Search operations are non-blocking `SELECT` queries on the SQLite database.\n- Since SQLite is in WAL (Write-Ahead Logging) mode, readers do not block writers, and writers do not block readers.\n- The `asyncio.Lock` in `database.py` ensures that multiple concurrent writes (from crawler workers) are serialized, while search queries remain performant and responsive during crawl operations.\n```')
