AgentFinish(thought='Failed to parse LLM response', output='FILE: architecture.md\n```text\n# Architecture Specification: Async Mini Search Engine\n\n## 1. Single-Event-Loop Lifecycle\n- The application runs entirely within the `asyncio.run()` context initiated in `main.py`.\n- No `threading` or `multiprocessing` modules are permitted.\n- All I/O (HTTP requests via `aiohttp`, SQLite operations via `aiosqlite` or `run_in_executor`) must be awaited.\n- The `main.py` entry point initializes the database, starts the crawler task, and enters an `asyncio.Queue`-based CLI loop.\n\n## 2. Public APIs\n\n### database.py\n- `Database(path: str)`: Initializes connection.\n- `async def setup()`: Enables WAL mode and creates the schema (replaces the failed `init` call).\n- `async def insert_document(url: str, content: str)`: Uses a shared `asyncio.Lock` to serialize writes.\n- `async def search(query: str) -> List[Dict]`: Performs read-only queries (non-blocking).\n- `async def is_crawled(url: str) -> bool`: Checks existence in the index.\n\n### crawler_service.py\n- `Crawler(db: Database, max_workers: int, queue_size: int)`:\n  - `async def start(seed_urls: List[str])`: Spawns worker tasks using `asyncio.create_task`.\n  - `async def worker()`: Consumes from `asyncio.Queue`, fetches via `aiohttp`, and writes to `db`.\n  - `async def add_url(url: str)`: Adds to queue if not already in `db` or queue.\n\n### main.py\n- `async def main()`: Orchestrates the lifecycle, calls `await db.setup()`.\n- `async def cli_loop()`: Handles user input for search queries while the crawler runs in the background.\n\n## 3. Crawl State Transitions\n- `PENDING`: URL added to `asyncio.Queue`.\n- `PROCESSING`: URL popped from queue, `aiohttp` request in progress.\n- `DONE`: Content parsed and committed to SQLite; URL marked as visited in the database.\n\n## 4. Duplicate Prevention & Back-pressure\n- **Duplicate Prevention**: Before adding a URL to the `asyncio.Queue`, the crawler calls `db.is_crawled(url)`. A `set` of "in-flight" URLs is maintained in memory to prevent duplicate queueing of URLs currently being processed.\n- **Back-pressure**: The `asyncio.Queue` is initialized with a `maxsize`. If the queue is full, `crawler.add_url()` will await until space is available, naturally slowing down the discovery process.\n\n## 5. Concurrent Search & Crawl\n- SQLite WAL (Write-Ahead Logging) mode allows multiple readers to access the database simultaneously while a single writer (protected by `asyncio.Lock`) performs updates.\n- The `main.py` CLI loop runs as a persistent task. Because the crawler and the CLI loop are both `asyncio` tasks, the event loop switches context between them during I/O waits, ensuring the search interface remains responsive even during heavy crawl activity.\n```', text='FILE: architecture.md\n```text\n# Architecture Specification: Async Mini Search Engine\n\n## 1. Single-Event-Loop Lifecycle\n- The application runs entirely within the `asyncio.run()` context initiated in `main.py`.\n- No `threading` or `multiprocessing` modules are permitted.\n- All I/O (HTTP requests via `aiohttp`, SQLite operations via `aiosqlite` or `run_in_executor`) must be awaited.\n- The `main.py` entry point initializes the database, starts the crawler task, and enters an `asyncio.Queue`-based CLI loop.\n\n## 2. Public APIs\n\n### database.py\n- `Database(path: str)`: Initializes connection.\n- `async def setup()`: Enables WAL mode and creates the schema (replaces the failed `init` call).\n- `async def insert_document(url: str, content: str)`: Uses a shared `asyncio.Lock` to serialize writes.\n- `async def search(query: str) -> List[Dict]`: Performs read-only queries (non-blocking).\n- `async def is_crawled(url: str) -> bool`: Checks existence in the index.\n\n### crawler_service.py\n- `Crawler(db: Database, max_workers: int, queue_size: int)`:\n  - `async def start(seed_urls: List[str])`: Spawns worker tasks using `asyncio.create_task`.\n  - `async def worker()`: Consumes from `asyncio.Queue`, fetches via `aiohttp`, and writes to `db`.\n  - `async def add_url(url: str)`: Adds to queue if not already in `db` or queue.\n\n### main.py\n- `async def main()`: Orchestrates the lifecycle, calls `await db.setup()`.\n- `async def cli_loop()`: Handles user input for search queries while the crawler runs in the background.\n\n## 3. Crawl State Transitions\n- `PENDING`: URL added to `asyncio.Queue`.\n- `PROCESSING`: URL popped from queue, `aiohttp` request in progress.\n- `DONE`: Content parsed and committed to SQLite; URL marked as visited in the database.\n\n## 4. Duplicate Prevention & Back-pressure\n- **Duplicate Prevention**: Before adding a URL to the `asyncio.Queue`, the crawler calls `db.is_crawled(url)`. A `set` of "in-flight" URLs is maintained in memory to prevent duplicate queueing of URLs currently being processed.\n- **Back-pressure**: The `asyncio.Queue` is initialized with a `maxsize`. If the queue is full, `crawler.add_url()` will await until space is available, naturally slowing down the discovery process.\n\n## 5. Concurrent Search & Crawl\n- SQLite WAL (Write-Ahead Logging) mode allows multiple readers to access the database simultaneously while a single writer (protected by `asyncio.Lock`) performs updates.\n- The `main.py` CLI loop runs as a persistent task. Because the crawler and the CLI loop are both `asyncio` tasks, the event loop switches context between them during I/O waits, ensuring the search interface remains responsive even during heavy crawl activity.\n```')
