AgentFinish(thought='Failed to parse LLM response', output='FILE: architecture.md\n```text\n# Database Public API\nThe database module exposes the following public APIs:\n- `async def connect()`: Establishes a connection to the SQLite database with WAL mode enabled.\n- `async def create_index()`: Creates the necessary tables for the search index.\n- `async def insert_url(url)`: Inserts a URL into the database.\n- `async def get_url(url)`: Retrieves a URL from the database.\n- `async def update_url(url, status)`: Updates the status of a URL in the database.\n- `async def search(query)`: Searches for query in the database and returns relevant results.\n\n# Crawler Service Public API\nThe crawler service module exposes the following public APIs:\n- `async def crawl_url(url)`: Crawls a given URL and updates the database with the result.\n- `async def start_crawler()`: Starts the crawler service with a bounded in-memory queue and worker count.\n- `async def stop_crawler()`: Stops the crawler service.\n\n# Main Public API\nThe main module exposes the following public APIs:\n- `async def main()`: Starts the interactive CLI and event loop.\n\n# Single-Event-Loop Lifecycle\n1. The event loop is created in the main module using `asyncio.get_event_loop()`.\n2. The database connection is established using `database.connect()`.\n3. The crawler service is started using `crawler_service.start_crawler()`.\n4. The interactive CLI is started using `main.main()`.\n5. The event loop runs until the user stops the application.\n\n# Crawl State Transitions\nThe crawl state transitions are as follows:\n- `pending`: The URL is added to the queue and waiting to be crawled.\n- `processing`: The URL is being crawled.\n- `done`: The URL has been crawled and the result is updated in the database.\n\n# Duplicate URL Prevention\nTo prevent duplicate URLs from being crawled, the following rules are applied:\n- Before adding a URL to the queue, the database is checked to see if the URL has already been crawled.\n- If the URL has already been crawled, it is not added to the queue.\n\n# Queue Back-Pressure Rules\nTo prevent the queue from growing indefinitely, the following rules are applied:\n- The queue has a bounded size.\n- When the queue is full, new URLs are not added until space becomes available.\n\n# Search While Crawling\nSearch works while crawling is active by using the following approach:\n- The search function uses the database to retrieve relevant results.\n- The database is updated in real-time as the crawler service crawls new URLs.\n- The search function returns the latest results from the database.\n```', text='FILE: architecture.md\n```text\n# Database Public API\nThe database module exposes the following public APIs:\n- `async def connect()`: Establishes a connection to the SQLite database with WAL mode enabled.\n- `async def create_index()`: Creates the necessary tables for the search index.\n- `async def insert_url(url)`: Inserts a URL into the database.\n- `async def get_url(url)`: Retrieves a URL from the database.\n- `async def update_url(url, status)`: Updates the status of a URL in the database.\n- `async def search(query)`: Searches for query in the database and returns relevant results.\n\n# Crawler Service Public API\nThe crawler service module exposes the following public APIs:\n- `async def crawl_url(url)`: Crawls a given URL and updates the database with the result.\n- `async def start_crawler()`: Starts the crawler service with a bounded in-memory queue and worker count.\n- `async def stop_crawler()`: Stops the crawler service.\n\n# Main Public API\nThe main module exposes the following public APIs:\n- `async def main()`: Starts the interactive CLI and event loop.\n\n# Single-Event-Loop Lifecycle\n1. The event loop is created in the main module using `asyncio.get_event_loop()`.\n2. The database connection is established using `database.connect()`.\n3. The crawler service is started using `crawler_service.start_crawler()`.\n4. The interactive CLI is started using `main.main()`.\n5. The event loop runs until the user stops the application.\n\n# Crawl State Transitions\nThe crawl state transitions are as follows:\n- `pending`: The URL is added to the queue and waiting to be crawled.\n- `processing`: The URL is being crawled.\n- `done`: The URL has been crawled and the result is updated in the database.\n\n# Duplicate URL Prevention\nTo prevent duplicate URLs from being crawled, the following rules are applied:\n- Before adding a URL to the queue, the database is checked to see if the URL has already been crawled.\n- If the URL has already been crawled, it is not added to the queue.\n\n# Queue Back-Pressure Rules\nTo prevent the queue from growing indefinitely, the following rules are applied:\n- The queue has a bounded size.\n- When the queue is full, new URLs are not added until space becomes available.\n\n# Search While Crawling\nSearch works while crawling is active by using the following approach:\n- The search function uses the database to retrieve relevant results.\n- The database is updated in real-time as the crawler service crawls new URLs.\n- The search function returns the latest results from the database.\n```')
